04947nam a22007215i 9780691190174DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911901747 a10.1515/97806911901742doi  a(DE-B1597)501648  a(OCoLC)1076426942  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBL1140.4.B436bP87 2005eb 7aREL0320002bisacsh04a294.5/9252231 aSchweig, Graham M., eauthor.10aDance of Divine Love :bIndia's Classic Sacred Love Story: The Rasa Lila of Krishna /cGraham M. Schweig. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2005  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tForeword / rHein, Norvin -- tAcknowledgments -- tPronunciation -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction The Sacred Love Story -- tPart I Poems from the Bhagavata Purana -- tDance of Divine Love: Rasa Lila -- tSong of the Flute: Venu Gita -- tSong of the Black Bee: Bhramara Gita -- tPart II Textual Illuminations -- t1. Background of the Text -- t2. Aspects of the Story -- t3. Messages of the Text -- tPart III Notes and Comments -- tIntroduction -- tAct One -- tAct Two -- tAct Three -- tAct Four -- tAct Five -- tPart IV The Sanskrit Text -- tIntroduction -- tAct One -- tAct Two -- tAct Three -- tAct Four -- tAct Five -- tAppendix 1 Note on Translation -- tAppendix 2 Poetic Meters in Sanskrit Text -- tAppendix 3 Synoptic Analysis of the Rasa Lila -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe heart of this book is a dramatic love poem, the Rasa Lila, which is the ultimate focal point of one of the most treasured Sanskrit texts of India, the Bhagavata Purana. Judged a literary masterpiece by Indian and Western scholars alike, this work of poetic genius and soaring religious vision is one of the world's greatest sacred love stories and, as Graham Schweig clearly demonstrates, should be regarded as India's Song of Songs. The story presents the supreme deity as the youthful and amorous cowherd, Krishna, who joins his beloved maidens in an enchanting and celebratory "dance of divine love." Schweig introduces this work of exquisite poetry and profound theology to the Western world in the form of a luminous translation and erudite scholarly treatment. His book explores the historical context and literary genre of the work and elucidates the aesthetic and emotional richness of the composition, highlighting poignant details of this drama of divine love. Schweig illuminates the religious dimensions and ethical nuances of the drama, drawing widely from the commentaries and esoteric vision of masters of the Caitanya school of Vaishnavism, a prominent devotional Hindu tradition. Themes such as transcendence of death through love, the yoga of devotion, the contrast between worldly love and passionate love for God, and the dialectical tension between ethical boundaries and boundless love are presented. The final event of the Rasa dance, the author concludes, presents a dynamic symbol of supreme love that provides the basis for a theological vision of genuine religious pluralism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aRāsa līlā (Dance) 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691190174zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691190174.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  a